\begin{align*}
z + \frac{17z + 6\overline{z}}{|z|^2} &= 6, \\
\overline{z} + \frac{6z - 17\overline{z}}{|z|^2} &= 0.
\end{align*}

Now, notice that $|z|^2 = z\overline{z} = a^2 + b^2$. We can simplify the equations to
\begin{align*}
z + \frac{17z + 6\overline{z}}{z\overline{z}} &= 6, \\
\overline{z} + \frac{6z - 17\overline{z}}{z\overline{z}} &= 0.
\end{align*}

Multiplying both sides of the first equation by $z\overline{z}$ gives
\begin{align*}
z^2\overline{z} + 17z + 6\overline{z} &= 6z\overline{z}, 
\end{align*}
and multiplying both sides of the second equation by $z\overline{z}$ gives
\begin{align*}
\overline{z} z\overline{z} + 6z - 17\overline{z} &= 0.
\end{align*}

Adding the two new equations together gives
\begin{align*}
z^2\overline{z} + z\overline{z} + 6z &= 6z\overline{z},
\end{align*}
or equivalently
\begin{align*}
z(z + 1) + 6z &= 6z\overline{z}.
\end{align*}

At this point, we notice that the right side of the equation is the real part of $z^2$, and the left side is a linear equation in $z$. Therefore, the set of solutions $z$ is the set of complex numbers of the form $a(1 + i)$ where $a$ is real.

Let $z = a(1+i) = a + ai$ be a solution satisfying this form. Then plug into the original equations gives
\begin{align*}
a + ai + \frac{17a + 6ai}{a^2 + a^2} &= 6, \\
ai + \frac{6a - 17ai}{a^2 + a^2} &= 0,
\end{align*}
which simplifies to
\begin{align*}
a + \frac{17 + 6i}{2} &= 6, \\
ai - \frac{17 + 6i}{2} &= 0.
\end{align*}

Solving these equations gives $a = 2$ and $a = -1$. Therefore, the solutions are $2 + 2i$ and $-1-i$, so the sum of all solutions is $2 + 2 + (-1) + (-1) = \boxed{2}$.```

